title: Bethel Defends Democracy Rally: Supporting Military Families' Service and Sacrifice
description:
Join us for our 12th consecutive rally to Defend Democracy in beautiful downtown Bethel. While our overall theme is Defending Democracy, each week we pick a specific focus. On Saturday May 24th, 11am -12:30pm, our focus will be on Supporting Military Families’ Service and Sacrifice. 

We will be honoring the service and sacrifice of the members of our active duty Armed Forces and their families.  As it is Memorial Day Weekend we will also be paying tribute to those who paid the ultimate price in service to this country.  

We will highlight some of the issues military families face including food insecurity, obtaining mental health services for the service member and their spouse, and cuts in experienced high ranking officers leaving troops without appropriate leadership.

Vietnam veteran John Paul Trudeau, who experienced firsthand, the loss of friends and brothers in arms, will be our guest speaker.

Several live musical selections will be performed by Barry Saroff.  Lorraine McGuire will lead a sing-a-long of God Bless America.

The rally is non-partisian. All are welcome.

There will be something for everyone. We'll have speakers, we'll rally with our signs, we'll take a short march and we'll have live music. We also like to end each week with a sing-a-long.

A sign-making table will also be available, complete with all the necessary supplies, for young and old to make signs for the rally.

We also collect a non-perishable food item for our local food pantry each week.  Some special requests from the food pantry:

-  Spices, Coffee and Baking supplies are always needed.

-   Individually packaged items. so if you bought a variety pack of something like granola bars or instant oatmeal and discovered there's a flavor you won't eat, please give us the individual packs out of box.

-  Empty egg cartons- Any style, so long as they're clean.

-  SMALL empty detergent bottles

Note: Rally is rain or shine.

There are 2 small benches at the square and we will have a limited number of camping chairs. Please bring your own lawn or camping chair if you'd like.

We also ask that you park at one of the four public parking lots. The lot that is very close to the rally location, PT Barnum Square, is behind the municipal center.  A map will be emailed to you after registration.

Although all street parking is public, we ask that you please do not park in the limited parking spots in front of our local businesses, but definitely enjoy our beautiful towns restaurants and shops after the rally! 
Thank you 😊

title: Independence Day Resistance Rally - Indivisible - Democracy Action Network
description:
"No Kings Since 1776" - Standing Against Autocracy

Join us on July 5th for a peaceful march and rally to reaffirm our commitment to democratic principles and stand against the threats of autocracy. As we gather just after Independence Day, we honor our founders' revolutionary spirit and their rejection of monarchical rule.

Why July 5th?

While the nation celebrates on the 4th, we gather the day after to remind ourselves that independence isn't just a historical achievement—it's an ongoing responsibility. title: Ballots, Barriers & the Battle for Election Integrity (Speaker: Secretary of State Shenna Bellows) ­
description:
Indivisible Cumberland County welcomes Maine Secretary of State Shenna Bellows for a public discussion on election integrity. Bellows will speak about her role in protecting Maine’s elections, including her 2023 decision to bar former President Donald Trump from Maine’s primary ballot under the 14th Amendment’s insurrection clause—a decision later overturned by the U.S. Supreme Court. She will also discuss her office’s ongoing work to increase election transparency, including livestreaming ballot tabulations and educating voters on Maine’s ranked-choice voting process.

Bellows will also address the proposed November referendum that would impose new photo ID requirements and restrict absentee voting by eliminating two days of early voting, limiting drop boxes, and tightening absentee ballot requests. She has raised concerns that these changes could create barriers for seniors, rural voters, and others who rely on current absentee voting options. The event offers attendees the chance to learn more about these proposed changes and ask questions about Maine’s efforts to ensure secure and accessible elections.

A grassroots pressure event, or birddog, is when folks show up at events and ask a public official a question to gain knowledge about their position on a particular topic. In Maryland, we'll be using this grassroots pressure tactic to understand Governor Wes Moore's position on gas plants in Maryland and to push to keep new gas plants out of Maryland.

title: Unite for Veterans, Unite for America
description:
On June 6, 2025, veterans, patriots, and supporters will gather in Houston under the banner of 50501-Houston to honor the legacy of D-Day and to protest in defense of the U.S. Constitution, stand up for veterans' rights, and demand full support for those who have served.

The rally will call on the Federal Government to rehire wrongfully terminated employees and to fully fund and implement the PACT Act, a historic piece of legislation that directly affects the health and well-being of veterans exposed to toxic substances during military service.

“This is more than a protest—it’s a movement of accountability and unity,” organizers said. “We stand for the Constitution, we stand for veterans, and we will not be silent.”

What Is the PACT Act?
The Sergeant First Class (SFC) Heath Robinson Honoring Our Promise to Address Comprehensive Toxics (PACT) Act is the most significant expansion of VA health care and benefits in decades. It ensures that veterans exposed to toxic substances—including burn pits, Agent Orange, and radiation—receive the care and compensation they deserve.

Key Provisions of the PACT Act Include:

Expanded eligibility for VA health care for veterans of Vietnam, Gulf War, and post-9/11 eras

20+ new “presumptive conditions” linked to toxic exposure

Automatic coverage for conditions like cancers and respiratory illnesses

Required toxic exposure screenings for all enrolled veterans

Additional funding for VA research, staffing, and treatment systems

Veterans are encouraged to file claims now and check their eligibility for new or expanded benefits under this law.

Why This Matters:
Tens of thousands of veterans are affected by toxic exposures. Without full funding and government follow-through, the promises made by the PACT Act could fall short. That’s why 50501-Houston is calling on all Americans to unite on June 6—to honor those who fought for freedom and fight now for those living with the aftermath of service.

title: Wheeler Salmonberry Trail Ground Building
description:
**Join The Salmonberry Trail in our exciting ground breaking event at Waterfront Park in Wheeler!**

The City of Wheeler is excited to announce that we are taking the first steps toward revitalization of Wheeler’s section of the Salmonberry Trail through partnership with the Salmonberry Trail Foundation and Tillamook Coast Visitors Association. We will be holding a **Ground Building event and ceremony on July 12, 2025 from 1:00-5:00 PM.** We truly could not be more excited for the recreational opportunities this trail will provide for our community.

This transformative project holds the potential to deliver lasting, meaningful benefits to our community. By linking the Willamette Valley to the Coast, it will not only strengthen regional connectivity but also invigorate rural tourism and empower small businesses. It champions public health and safe, active transportation options while expanding equitable access to the outdoors for all residents. Most importantly, it lays the foundation for sustainable infrastructure that will support our economy, environment, and quality of life for generations to come.

We will have local vendors, music, games, and a ribbon cutting ceremony celebrating the beginning of this coastal section of the trail. 
- July 12th, 1PM - 5PM
- Waterfront Park (500 Marine Dr, Wheeler, OR 97147)

---
**ABOUT THE SALMONBERRY TRAIL**
The Salmonberry Trail is an 82-mile multi-use path transforming a historic rail line into Oregon’s next big adventure. Connecting communities from the Willamette Valley to the coast, the trail will provide safe routes for recreation and education, expand economic opportunities, and improve public health. In partnership with local organizations, it will offer unique educational programs while promoting outdoor activity and conservation, making it a cornerstone of community development and environmental stewardship across the state.

**Wheeler Demonstration Project – Salmonberry Trail**
The Wheeler Demonstration Project is a short, high-impact segment of the Salmonberry Trail located in downtown Wheeler. This 1,800-foot trail segment runs north from Rector Street, across Hemlock Street, and along the bay side of the Oregon Coast Scenic Railway tracks adjacent to Botts Marsh. It features a compacted gravel path for pedestrians, designed to enhance safety and encourage walking in the downtown area.
Developed in partnership with the City of Wheeler, Oregon Coast Scenic Railway, Lower Nehalem Community Trust, and the Salmonberry Trail Foundation, the project supports local economic activity, offers environmental education through interpretive signage, and provides a model for similar efforts in other communities along the trail corridor.
